column1: 16022;instagram;2019-02-20 17:15:01;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner

was having a debate with @novarflip and my bro @phoenixdaicefire re the rape culture of women here in the uk

part pf the problem i feel is a lack of education as to what constitutes as ‚Äòrape‚Äô ie any situation when you‚Äôre forcing yourself on someone sexually without consent!! my opinion is that a root solution could be to decrease the objectification of women in mainstream media. i say that because in many industries
column2: #porn advertising #entertainment #films #music that the majority of women are seen a objects of desire and #sex ‚Äòjust to look good‚Äô often getting stupid interview questions
column3: damsel-in-destress type roles in film and generally roles that focus too heavily on appearance. films like #blackpanther are dope for their portrayal of strong #blackwomen ‚úäüèø‚úäüèø also i feel that the porn industry shapes alot of male views (and women) on women and has us seeing women as nothing more than sex objects from a young age. this really has a big impact i feel on us men tbh
column4: as this comes about at a crucial stage of our development.

column2: schools should look at addressing more life skills. not just sex education but relationship education as a whole (on a very basic general level). #womensright #women #relationships #agenda #metoo

column1: 16319;instagram;2019-02-20 13:42:37;FALSE;"according to the national sexual violence resource center * 1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
* in the united stares 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance.
* 52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger.
* 49.5% of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female
column2: and 9% are male * in 8 out of 10 cases of rape

column1: * 8% of rapes occur while the victim is at work.
the problem of sexual violence runs rampant
column2: and yet rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. of the remaining 37% that are reported less than 10% are instances of false reporting. the facts are clear
column3: and still the culture that would rather victims of sexually based crimes remain silent prevails.

column1: 16477;instagram;2019-02-20 10:44:32;FALSE;"#wouldyoubeinterested? i've been wanting to share this workshop with you since #metoo and love to hear if you would be interested.

it's a high energy clearing workshop working with sexuality and body love and feeling more comfortable with your own body (and sex). and it clears any past life vows of chastity that sometimes prevents people from stepping into a relationship.
it will have a bonus mary magdalene meditation. the mary magdalene meditation is also part of the 7 days of goddesses healing journey.
mary magdalene is a representative of the suppressed divine feminine & female qualities.
i'm not offering this energy work as a solution to whats's been deeply rooted in our society
column2: but as a tool to heal for those who need it.

she is specifically helpful in overcoming matters of (sexual) abuse and women being unheard
column2: go unseen and treated differently based on their gender.

column2: because of society or what has happened to you in connecting with men that tried to prey on you.

column1: since i'd love everyone to be able to join: the 1-hour workshop with past vow clearing and bonus meditation  would be offered as a $19 early bird with lifetime access.

column1: 16530;instagram;2019-02-20 08:41:11;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day

column1: i heard endearingly shared with a survivor of rape and child molestation. as i listened to the conversation
column2: the inside of me cringed knowing that while they meant well by saying ‚Äúthis too shall pass‚Äù that statement simply wasn‚Äôt true in the context. as a survivor of domestic violence i often meet with
column4: women who have experienced abuse connecting them to resources and simply being a friend. my best friend volunteers with dallas area rape crisis center and spends her time sitting with women and men through rape kits and connecting survivors to free therapy and additional resources to pursue healing and justice. (this is the side of @turningpaiges_ you do not see online.)

column2: what happened to you will never just pass. you will never be who you were before the abuse happened. you will never know who you would have been if you had never been abused. there may be seasons of your life that you blackout the trauma in an effort to cope but the memories don‚Äôt ever really leave you. and that is okay. bc while what happened to you may never leave you
column3: you will one day learn to be in control of the triggers that once controlled you. even after abuse
column4: you do still have the power within you to one day stop longing for the old you and you will learn to love who you have become after abuse. you will always carry the truth of what happened to you but you do not have to always hold onto the pain. maybe the next time a survivor shares with you their pain
column5: maybe just listen. the bible talks about mourning with those who mourn. maybe reassure that survivor that they are not alone. maybe ask them how you can be there for them before you give a prescription to a pain you know nothing about. maybe tell them it wasn‚Äôt their fault and that they too are loved. maybe don‚Äôt just tell them this will pass but assure them that you will be with them through whatever weather the trauma brings. bc the good news is
column6: we serve a god that makes all things brand new. he won‚Äôt make us the old us
column7: but he does give us the opportunity to be made brand new with no shame or condemnation for where we‚Äôve been. resurrection wasn‚Äôt just for jesus ‚Äîit‚Äôs for you";;en;;@turningpaiges_;;;;0;;tristenpaige;Tristen Paige;;0;False;33;0;0;163;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/813fd00f15a3513a9bb30d5e1f2f240f/5D071E7C/t51.2885-15/e35/51626758_790915084575790_3126204956364381279_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"this too shall pass...

column1: 16766;instagram;2019-02-20 03:31:02;FALSE;"have you ever been impacted by someone's story in a way that changed your life? i have time and time again. #transformationtuesday
our stories have so much potential to impact the world. i've been thinking about what that means for me
column2: especially as i've been on this incredible journey of healing for the past 5 years. i look back at all of my experiences both good and bad
column3: and feel thankful to have the capacity to allow those experiences to inform my decisions and thoughts.

column1: i know that the most important thing that i can do with the rest of my life is to allow myself to voice my truth so that i can help other people. it's one thing say ""if i can do it then you can too"" but it's another and even more important to help people take those steps.

i've lived enough life for ten people and if i can help just one person find their true potential and more importantly find the capacity to love themselves i will die knowing that i did my best. that's all i want and that's what i aim to do and i believe in my heart that my story
column2: my journey is the catalyst to that.

column1: but i was dead. dead things don't love.
you'll never get those days back.
they thought they broke you small enough to fit into their monochromatic mold.
but when you were pulled out from beneath the ground there were people who against all odds
loved you as purely as they knew how.
then there were people that didn't.
their desires were dark and fervent
a damaging preoccupation and words that were true at all the wrong times.
it was a sweet relief falling into those patterns.
gazing wistfully at the flowers littered on top of the mound of dirt above your grave and wondering if there's anything left down there in the dark.
nearly hating the people that dragged you towards the achingly bright sky.

the broken doll and the sorority king.
but blood is thicker than water.

we clutch our stories to our chests like priceless gems
afraid that if we shared our brokenness it would diminish its value...it would diminish our value.

column1: instead of anchoring us together against a sheer cliff in the blackest of nights.

did you think we could hide our faces beneath the charade?
now turn very carefully and raise your eyes to mine.

column2: but in time you will learn to recognize me.

and the sound you hear is blood coursing through my new heart.

column2: the mother of the #metoo movement has been a powerful and prominent force in women's rights and activism for those who identity as survivors. ‚àÜ

column1: let's talk about rape and sexual assault. rape is not sex. sex is about connection and rape is about power and control. as women in these bodies in this world in this time in space
column2: we all deal with the reality and truth of a society that sexualizes women for the pleasure of men. #metoo is powerful because it brings us together in solidarity. it bridges the gap of gender
column3: race and religion. it stands to the fact that our bodies have been abused by another in a sexual way. i won't tell my story here
column4: right now but i will say #metoo. on this full moon i carry during my travels a token from an assault i experienced about 4 years ago. i carry this token to release it
column6: to engange in ceremony the energy of this person who misused their power and prayed on someone vulnerable who was afraid to use their voice and for me this time around to take back control. i engage in ceremony to bring to fruition to reap the harvest all i have gained from this experience and to release all that no longer deserves space in my heart. i say #metoo because i'm no longer afraid to use my voice and move on from my traumas and stories for they are a potent form of advocacy. i may not be ready to share my stories in full and that's okay. wherever we each are on our journey is ok so long as we honor it. ¬∞

column3: ""swimming with giants"". i wrote the piece mostly about feeling small & underestimated
column4: swimming in this sea of what feels like giants - coming home to the sweet relief of this vibrant community that seems mysteriously immune to the dull dragging of day to day - it speaks on how i feel there are beautiful beings much bigger than giants- there are gods. it's good. and it's inspired by the sugar shack - where i live now. we are still fundraising for our roof!! help if you can. if you can't- spread the word. you never know who has $5 to spare and here we go throwing it in and growing within. thank you to everyone who's donated so far. come through
